<DOC><DOCNO> AP900314-0063 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-14-90 1133EST</FILEID><FIRST>r w PM-SpacePoll     03-14 0272</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Space Poll,260</SECOND><HEAD>Fewer Than Two of Three Americans Favor Lunar Base and MarsMissions</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Approval of the United States space program isat an all-time high, but fewer than two out of three Americansfavor the lunar base and Mars missions proposed by President Bush,according to a survey released today.   Eighty percent of the American people favor the space program,said the nationwide telephone poll of 1,200 registered votersconducted by Market Opinion Research. The poll was commissioned byRockwell International Corporation, one of the biggest aerospacemanufacturers and builder of the space shuttles.   The survey, which has a margin of error of plus or minus 2.8percent, showed approval rating of the space program continuing torise from 56 percent in May 1978. The space station, which isentering the building phase, was favored by 74 percent of thosepolled, up from 69 percent last March. The National Aero-Spaceplane, still on the drawing boards, is favored by 70 percent, upfrom 57 percent last year.   On the 20th anniversary last July of man's first landing on themoon, Bush outlined a goal of returning to the moon and sendingmanned expeditions to Mars early in the next century. Only 64percent of the poll respondents favored the lunar proposal and only62 percent favored going to Mars.   While 85 percent of the respondents believe it is important thatthe United States take the lead in developing new technologies forthose programs and for monitoring the environment, only 56 percentagreed that the government should spend ``whatever is necessary''to maintain its position of leadership.</TEXT></DOC>